95 /**
96 Lifecycle management of internal temporary tables.
97
98 An internal temporary table is represented by a TABLE_SHARE object.
99
100 The interface to an internal temporary table is through one or more TABLE
101 objects, of which at most one TABLE object is a writer object, the remaining
102 TABLE objects are reader objects. Each TABLE object points to the TABLE_SHARE.
103 TABLE_SHARE::ref_count counts the number of TABLE objects that points to it.
104
105 The TABLE, TABLE_SHARE and associated objects (e.g Field objects) are
106 created in a dedicated mem_root. This mem_root is deleted when the TABLE_SHARE
107 object is deleted.
108
109 Initially, an internal temporary table is created with one TABLE_SHARE
110 object and one TABLE object. The table is created with no file handler
111 (storage engine) and in the "deleted" state. Later, more TABLE objects may
112 be created against the table, and TABLE_SHARE::ref_count is increased.
113
114 An internal temporary table may be instantiated and used multiple times,
115 typically once per execution of a statement.
116
117 To instantiate a table, call instantiate_tmp_table(). This function will
118 first assign and lock a storage engine using setup_tmp_table_handler(). The
119 locked engine is assigned to TABLE_SHARE::db_plugin and the file handler is
120 assigned to TABLE::file. After this, calling TABLE::has_storage_handler()
121 reports true.
122
123 After this, the table contents is created by calling TABLE::file->create()
124 and the table is opened by calling open_tmp_table(), which itself calls
125 TABLE::file->ha_open(), and sets the TABLE::created flag.
126
127 Thus, opening a temporary table is a two-stage operation:
128 1. assign and lock a storage engine, and
129 2. create the table contents.
130
131 Since a temporary table may be in any of the two stages, we use two
132 counter members in the TABLE_SHARE to count the number of TABLEs in each
133 of the stages: tmp_handler_count and tmp_open_count.
134 tmp_handler_count is incremented in setup_tmp_table_handler().
135 tmp_open_count is incremented in open_tmp_table().
136
137 To open an already instantiated table, assign a storage handler by calling
138 setup_tmp_table_handler(), then call open_tmp_table() which will
139 again increment TABLE_SHARE::tmp_open_count and set TABLE::created.
140
141 Insert, update, delete and read rows using the active TABLE handlers.
142
143 After use, close all active TABLE handlers by calling close_tmp_table().
144 For simplicity, we may also call close_tmp_table() on a non-active TABLE,
145 as it will check whether a storage handler has been assigned.
146
147 If the table is created, TABLE_SHARE::tmp_open_count is decremented.
148 If there are no remaining active TABLE objects, delete the table contents
149 by calling TABLE::file->ha_drop_table(), otherwise close it by calling
150 TABLE::file->ha_close().
151 Set status of the TABLE to deleted and delete the storage handler.
152 If there are no remaining active tables and the storage engine is still
153 locked, unlock the plugin and disassociate it from the TABLE_SHARE object,
154 and decrement TABLE_SHARE::tmp_handler_count.
155
156 After the final instantiation of an internal temporary table, call
157 free_tmp_table() for all associated TABLE objects.
158
159 free_tmp_table() can only be called on a non-instantiated temporary table
160 (but handlers may be assigned for other TABLE objects to the same table)..
161 It will decrement TABLE_SHARE::ref_count and the final call will also
162 remove the temporary table's mem_root object.
163 */

712 /**
713 Moves to the end of the 'copy_func' array the elements which contain a
714 reference to an expression of the SELECT list of 'query_block'.
715 @param query_block query block to search in
716 @param[in,out] copy_func array to sort
717 */
718 918647 static void sort_copy_func(const Query_block *query_block,
719 Func_ptr_array *copy_func) {
720 /*
721 In the query_block->fields list, there are hidden elements first, then
722 non-hidden. Non-hidden are those of the SELECT list. Hidden ones are:
723 (a) those of GROUP BY, HAVING, ORDER BY
724 (b) those which have been extracted from higher-level elements (of the
725 SELECT, GROUP BY, etc) by split_sum_func() (when aggregates are
726 involved).
727
728 Note that the clauses in (a) are allowed to reference a non-hidden
729 expression through an alias (e.g. "SELECT a+2 AS x GROUP BY x+3"). The
730 clauses in (b) can reference non-hidden expressions without aliases if they
731 have been generated in a query transformation (for example when transforming
732 an IN subquery to a correlated EXISTS subquery ("(x, y) IN (SELECT expr1,
733 expr2 ...)" -> "EXISTS (SELECT * ... HAVING x = expr1 AND y = expr2 ...").
734
735 Let's go through the process of writing to the tmp table
736 (MaterializeIterator).
737 (1) we switch to the REF_SLICE used to read from that tmp table
738 (2) we (copy_fields()) copy some columns from the
739 output of the previous step of execution (e.g. the join's output) to the
740 tmp table
741 (3) Next is copy_funcs(). It is meant to evaluate expressions and
742 store their values into the tmp table.
743 Because we advanced the REF_SLICE, when copy_funcs() evaluates an
744 expression which uses Item_ref, that Item_ref may point to a column of
745 the tmp table. It is thus important that this column has been filled
746 already. So the order of evaluation of expressions by copy_funcs() must
747 respect "dependencies".
748
749 It is incorrect to evaluate elements of (a) first if they refer to
750 non-hidden elements through aliases. It is incorrect to evaluate elements of
751 (b) first if they refer to non-hidden elements. So, we partition the
752 elements below, moving to the end the ones which reference other expressions
753 in the same query block. We use a stable partitioning
754 (std::stable_partition), to avoid disturbing any dependency already
755 reflected in the order.
756
757 A simpler and more robust solution would be to break the design that
758 hidden elements are always first in Query_block::fields: references
759 using aliases (in GROUP BY, HAVING, ORDER BY) would be added to
760 fields last (after the SELECT list); an inner element (split by
761 split_sum_func) would be added right before its containing element. That
762 would reflect dependencies naturally. But it is hard to implement, as
763 some code relies on the fact that non-hidden elements are last.
764
765 You may wonder why we need a (relatively complex) sort, instead of just
766 putting all the hidden elements last: With window functions,
767 it's possible to have a hidden element be an aggregate (produced by
768 split_sum_func) _and_ be materialized (into a further tmp table),
769 so we have to leave it at the beginning of the copy_func array.
770 Except if it contains an alias to an expression
771 of the SELECT list: in that case, the sorting will move it to the end,
772 but will also move the aliased expression, and their relative order
773 will remain unchanged thanks to stable_partition, so their evaluation
774 will be in the right order.
775
776 So we walk each item to copy, put the ones that don't reference other
777 expressions in the query block first, and put those that reference other
778 expressions last.
779 */

2459 /**
2460 If a MEMORY table gets full, create a disk-based table and copy all rows
2461 to this.
2462
2463 @param[in] thd THD reference
2464 @param[in] wtable Table reference being written to
2465 @param[in] error Reason why inserting into MEMORY table failed.
2466 @param[in] insert_last_record If true, the last record(table->record[0])
2467 is inserted into the newly created table after
2468 copying all the records from the temp table.
2469 If false, the last record is not inserted
2470 and the parameters ignore_last_dup, is_duplicate
2471 are ignored.
2472 @param[in] ignore_last_dup If true, ignore duplicate key error for last
2473 inserted key (see detailed description below).
2474 @param [out] is_duplicate If non-NULL and ignore_last_dup is true,
2475 return true if last key was a duplicate,
2476 and false otherwise.
2477
2478 @details
2479 Function can be called with any error code, but only HA_ERR_RECORD_FILE_FULL
2480 will be handled, all other errors cause a fatal error to be thrown.
2481 The function creates a disk-based temporary table, copies all records
2482 from the MEMORY table into this new table, deletes the old table and
2483 switches to use the new table within the table handle.
2484 The function uses table->record[1] as a temporary buffer while copying.
2485
2486 If the parameter insert_last_record is true, this function assumes that
2487 table->record[0] contains the row that caused the error when inserting
2488 into the MEMORY table (the "last row"). After all existing rows have been
2489 copied to the new table,the last row is attempted to be inserted as well.
2490 If ignore_last_dup is true, this row can be a duplicate of an existing row
2491 without throwing an error. If is_duplicate is non-NULL, an indication of
2492 whether the last row was a duplicate is returned.
2493
2494 If the parameter insert_last_record is false, this function makes no
2495 assumptions on the operation and will not try an insert of the last
2496 record(table->record[0]). The caller is expected to handle the operation
2497 after moving to disk.
2498
2499 @note that any index/scan access initialized on the MEMORY 'wtable' is not
2500 replicated to the on-disk table - it's the caller's responsibility.
2501 However, access initialized on other TABLEs, is replicated.
2502
2503 If 'wtable' has other TABLE clones (example: a multi-referenced or a
2504 recursive CTE), we convert all clones; if an error happens during conversion
2505 of clone B after successfully converting clone A, clone A and B will exit
2506 from the function with a TABLE_SHARE corresponding to the pre-conversion
2507 table ("old" TABLE_SHARE). So A will be inconsistent (for example
2508 s->db_type() will say "MEMORY" while A->file will be a disk-based engine).
2509 However, as all callers bail out, it is reasonable to think that they won't
2510 be using the TABLE_SHARE except in free_tmp_table(); and free_tmp_table()
2511 only uses properties of TABLE_SHARE which are common to the old and new
2512 object (reference counts, MEM_ROOT), so that should work.
2513 Solutions to fix this cleanly:
2514 - allocate new TABLE_SHARE on heap instead of on stack, to be able to
2515 exit with two TABLE_SHAREs (drawback: more heap memory consumption, and need
2516 to verify all exit paths are safe),
2517 - close all TABLEs if error (but then callers and cleanup code may be
2518 surprised to find already-closed tables so they would need fixing).
2519 To lower the risk of error between A and B: we expect most errors will
2520 happen when copying rows (e.g. read or write errors); so we convert 'wtable'
2521 (which does the row copying) first; if it fails, the A-B situation is
2522 avoided and we can properly exit with the old TABLE_SHARE.
2523
2524 @returns true if error.
2525 */
